# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-humanist-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The **2014 American immigration crisis** was a surge in unaccompanied children and women from the Northern Triangle of Central America (NTCA) seeking entrance to the United States in 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] According to U.S. law, an unaccompanied alien child refers to a person under 18 years of age, who has no lawful immigration status in the U.S., and who does not have a legal guardian to provide physical custody and care.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Between 2013 and 2014, the number of unaccompanied children apprehended at the border increased nearly 80%, from 38,759 in fiscal year 2013 to 68,541 in fiscal year 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Many of the children had no parent/legal guardian available to provide care or physical custody and quickly overwhelmed local border patrols.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] From 1980 onwards, the number of immigrants from Central America arriving to the United States has grown substantially.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] However, most of the people fleeing Central America are those whose countries are plagued by corruption, poverty, and murder.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The three countries from Central America with the highest numbers of migrants are Honduras, Guatemala, and El Salvador.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Other immigrants from different countries in Central America have seen a moderate decrease from 2010 to 2013.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] For example, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Panama, and Belize have not had as many immigrants as the other three leading countries in the time frame.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The three leading countries are the bulk immigrants coming to the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Honduras, El Salvador, and Guatemala make up 85 percent of those who arrive to the United States since the 1980s.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] During the Cold War, the United States backed violent anti-Communist forces throughout Latin America.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Academics claim that the violence and high murder rates in many of these countries is the direct legacy of the U.S. intervention on behalf of these anti-Communist forces stretching back into the 1950s with the Guatemalan coup d'état, which has shaped the contemporary refugee crisis.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In 2014, the reason this crisis was internationally covered by media outlets, was due to the fact that most of the immigrants were children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Most of these children cross through the Guatemala-Mexico border.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Most of these children also ride with other migrants atop a train called "La Bestia" (The Beast), which begins near the Guatemalan border, in Chiapas state, and goes to Mexico City.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] However, La Bestia has drawn international attention.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] This train route is the epicenter of mass extortion, mutilation, murder, robberies, rape, kidnapping, and sexual assault of Central American and other immigrants.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Immigrants do not report these crimes in fear of being deported back to their native countries.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] If these immigrant children managed to survive La Bestia and the cartels in Mexico, they now need to find "coyotes" to smuggle them across the Mexican-American border.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Most women and children from Central America simply crossed the Rio Grande and turned themselves in to the United States Border Patrol, relying on the belief, partly well founded, that United States immigration and refugee law made special provision for children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The large number of migrants entitled to hearings, counsel, and placement overwhelmed U.S. immigration courts and other government facilities.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The 2014 uptick in immigration was largely due to a surge in arrivals of Unaccompanied Minor Children (UAC's), predominately from Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador (the Northern Triangle of Central America).
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Beginning in the early 2000s, the Northern Triangle countries of Honduras, Guatemala, and El Salvador experienced an increase in violent crime that would continue for the next decade.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Although the homicide rates in all three countries had been on the decline since 2011, the murder rates El Salvador and Honduras remained among the highest in the world.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In early 2014, El Salvador experienced another uptick in violence after a gang truce between MS-13 and Barrio 18 began to collapse.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Many of the unaccompanied children reported being under the false impression that the Obama Administration was granting permits ("permisos") to children with family members in the US, as long as they arrived by June 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] It was later determined that these rumors, along with similar rumors about permisos for women who arrived with children, were being promulgated by human smugglers.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] While the rumors were false, there were in fact a number of policies in place that offered protection from removal to unaccompanied children from Central America.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] For women, as crime increased in the last decade, sexual assault and rape have become a prevalent issue in the Northern Triangle as well.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In 2014, 40 percent of the people fleeing were women compared to a low 27 percent in recent times.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The United Nations Special Rapporteur on Violence Against Women showed that in July 2014, the violent death of women in Honduras shot up at an alarming rate of 263% from 2005 to 2013, fueling the migration of women.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In 2013, 95% of the cases of these women go unsolved and women leaving Honduras also face the same risks on their journey.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Organized crime and drug-related violence in these countries have also increased danger for their citizens.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Since the 1980s, Colombian smugglers have used Central America, specifically Honduras, as a corridor to the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Children in schools are forced to smuggle drugs.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Drug trafficking has taken over these countries! as waves of gangsters were deported from the United States in the 90s.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Gangs like MS-13 have grown in size and power.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Young children are the most vulnerable as gangsters will offer the choice of working for them or leaving.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The presence of Mexican cartels has been a feature of illegal drug trade in Guatemala, where law enforcement presence is sparse and there is plenty of open land where planes smuggling cocaine can easily land.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In the Northern Triangle (Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador), studies have shown that 19 out of 20 murders will not result in prosecution.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In addition to violence and crime, food shortages and malnutrition continue to plague the region.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] It is estimated that half of Guatemalan children are chronically malnourished, resulting in stunted growth and eventually death.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] While these countries have some of the greatest potential for economic growth, inequality and general incompetency by the government has left these issues either underserved or unaddressed completely.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] To start the asylum process, an immigrant child must fill out and apply at their consulate with a **N-400** form to apply for naturalization, which includes a processing fee and civics test.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] After completing processing interviews to determine priority designation, a child undergoing American naturalization must complete form **DS-260** in order to apply for an immigrant visa and/or alien registration.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] By the time the naturalization process has been completed it will have taken on average 18–24 months, though in the last 5 years this has been brought down to an average of 10.2 months.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On June 26, 2014, Obama said that parents from Central America shouldn't send their children, with his reasoning being that they could be victims of human trafficking or injure themselves while making the journey.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On July 9, 2014, a hearing on the crisis was held by the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Craig Fugate, the Administrator of the Federal Emergency Management Agency in the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Department of Homeland Security, testified, "We are talking about large numbers of children, without their parents, who have arrived at our border—hungry, thirsty, exhausted, scared and vulnerable".
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Senator Dianne Feinstein compared the crisis to the American refusal to accept Jewish refugees from Nazi Germany aboard the MS *St.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] President Obama's request for additional funds was met in both houses of Congress by proposals to modify or eliminate the rights granted by the 2008 reauthorization of the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act of 2000.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] As most unaccompanied children from Central America do not attempt to avoid capture but turn themselves into the Border Patrol after entering the United States, they usually cross the Rio Grande into Texas.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The large number of children overwhelmed facilities in Texas in summer 2014 and some of the women and children were transferred to INS facilities in California.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In most instances this occurred without incident, but in Murrieta, California, on July 1, 2014, buses carrying immigrants to a Border Patrol facility were blocked by flag-waving protesters.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On July 15, 2014, in Oracle, Arizona, pro and con demonstrators faced off regarding possible use of a local facility to house immigrant children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The location of the shelters being used is confidential, but a local law enforcement officer had informed the community of the planned use of the facility.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Department of Justice reported in June 2014 that it will provide around 100 lawyers and paralegals for the rising number of children coming to the United States without parents or relatives.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Under this program, the federal government will issue $2 million in grants to compensate lawyers and paralegals representing unaccompanied children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Attorney General Eric Holder stated, "We're taking a historic step to strengthen our justice system and protect the rights of the most vulnerable members of society".
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The Obama administration estimated roughly 60,000 unaccompanied children would come across the border to the United States in 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On July 18, 2014, Massachusetts Governor Deval Patrick offered one of two locations to the federal government as temporary shelters for up to 1,000 children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] One was Camp Edwards, in Bourne on Cape Cod; the other was Westover Air Reserve Base in Chicopee.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On July 23, 2014, Senator Barbara Mikulski introduced the bill Emergency Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2014 (S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] 2648; 113th Congress), a bill that would appropriate supplemental funds for FY2014 to specified federal agencies and programs to respond to the increased apprehensions of unaccompanied minors along the southwestern border, fight wildfires, and support Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile defense system.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The bill would provide $2.7 billion in supplemental funding.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Hal Rogers introduced the bill "Making supplemental appropriations for the fiscal year ending September 30, 2014 (H.R.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] 5230; 113th Congress)" (also known as the "Secure the Southwest Border Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2014" and the "Secure the Southwest Border Act of 2014") into the United States House of Representatives.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] 5230 would provide supplemental FY2014 appropriations to several federal agencies for expenses related to the rise in unaccompanied alien children and alien adults accompanied by an alien minor at the southwest border.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The bill would also change the procedures for screening and processing unaccompanied alien children who arrive at the border from certain countries.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] 5230 would provide $659 million in supplemental funding.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] On July 30, 2014, President Barack Obama released a statement of administration policy stating that "his senior advisors would recommend he veto the bill" if it were presented to him for his signature.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The House was scheduled to vote on the bill on July 31, 2014, but the Republican leadership canceled the vote because it did not have enough votes to pass H.R.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The Department of Health and Human Services had opened three temporary shelters for children at military bases in Texas, Oklahoma, and California, but the sites were closed in August 2014 as the flow of migrant children declined and the capacity of permanent centers to house children was expanded.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] However, the new centers, such as the one in Artesia, New Mexico, may not offer facilities compatible with due process.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] After a lawsuit was filed by the ACLU about conditions at Artesia conditions there showed marked improvement.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In January 2014 the Department of Homeland Security sought a contractor to manage and transport approximately 65,000 Unaccompanied Alien Children (UAC) "ages infant to 17 years of age".
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The Department of Health and Human Services stated in its "Budget in Brief" that the expected annual number of arriving UAC had increased from 6,560 to an estimated 60,000 for fiscal year 2014, and the Government anticipated awarding a five-year contract to deal with them.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In October 2014, immigrant rights groups filed Freedom of Information Act ("FOIA") litigation to compel the release of documents regarding the use of the expedited removal process against families with children, including those detained at the family detention center in Artesia, New Mexico.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] 7311, William Wilberforce Trafficking Victims Protection Reauthorization Act of 2008, signed into law by George W.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Bush give substantial rights and protection to unaccompanied children from countries which do not have a common border with the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In November 2017, the Trump administration ended the Central American Minors Program which allowed eligible minors from the Northern Triangle to apply for the refugee resettlement or parole in the United States, thereby limiting the flow of Central Americans to the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Congress has so far granted $1.4 billion contingent on these Central American countries meeting security, corruption, and human rights requirements to receive assistance.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] When funding was first appropriated for these countries, funding was split fairly evenly between addressing economic and civil concerns and "rule of law" concerns regarding police and judicial institutions.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] So far none of these countries have met all of the legislative requirements to receive all of the funding allotted to them.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In a statement made on the inauguration of Jimmy Morales as the President of Guatemala, the Obama administration addressed certain criteria that the Northern Triangle countries (Honduras, El Salvador, Guatemala) would be expected to uphold in order to receive assistance from the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] These criteria have reflected long-standing obstacles for prosperity in these countries, particularly those relating to equality, human rights, and collecting government revenues needed to fund police.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] While funding for these efforts has been fairly consistent the past two years, the FY2018 budget proposed by President Trump would cut aid to these countries by roughly 30%.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] It is hard to know what the full implications of this cut to funding would be, but experts have claimed that it would most likely result in backsliding of any progress made in the governance of these countries.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Detention centers were reported overcrowding in the summer of 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] One cause of the influx of immigrants with children was word of mouth in Central America that families with children were not detained due to lack of facilities.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The facility in Dilley includes barrack-style housing, a school, a medical clinic, and other facilities.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] However, migrants in the detention centers were refused bond in order to deter other migrants.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In February 2015, a federal court, in a case under appeal, forbade use of deterrence of others as a consideration in refusing bond.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Jeh Johnson, Secretary of Homeland Security issued new regulations easing requirements for bonding out reducing the average stay in the facility to 22 days, and some detainees who have been detained 6 months or longer have been released.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Johnson believes maintaining some capacity to detain families is necessary to maintain deterrence.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus called for humane measures with respect to families and children fleeing violence in Central America and continued efforts to refine administrative policy with respect to the millions of undocumented immigrants living and working in the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] A 2014 *Mother Jones* article suggested that many of the unaccompanied children were attempting to escape abusive situations.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Analysis of Border Patrol statistics by the Director of the Regional Security Policy Program at the Washington Office on Latin America shows a correlation between gang-related killing of children in Central America, particularly San Pedro Sula in Honduras, and the surge in migration.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] According to the Immigrant Rights' Project of the American Civil Liberties Union, the Office of Refugee Resettlement (ORR) within the United States Department of Health and Human Services, the United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS), including U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Customs and Border Protection (CBP), and the Executive Office for Immigration Review (EOIR),(usually called the immigration courts), within the United States Department of Justice each have statutory responsibilities with respect to unaccompanied children from Central America.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The ACLU believes the stipulated settlement in *Flores v.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Meese*, which is a United States District Court for the Central District of California decision which sets out a nationwide policy concerning federal detention of any minor, also applies.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] While acknowledging suggestions that immigration reform may have helped prompt the influx of child migrants, the Obama administration has also focused attention on measures to be taken by the migrants' home countries to try to stop the flow.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In July 2014, President Obama met with the presidents of Guatemala, El Salvador, and Honduras to seek their cooperation in reducing migration of children and expediting returns.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In the summer of 2014, Mexico took actions to keep migrants from using freight trains ("La Bestia") to travel through Mexico.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] As of February 2015, the number of unaccompanied minors apprehended at the U.S. border, 12,509, during the previous 5 months had dropped while the number deported by Mexico to their home countries, 3,819, had risen by 56% year on year from the same period in fiscal year 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Conditions in Honduras had improved with a drop of about 20% in the homicide rate from 2012 to 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Since the placement of restrictions on illegal immigration through policies pursued by the Trump administration, the movement of people from Central America to the United States has shifted to Mexico.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The role of Mexico as a transit country between the Northern Triangle and the United States has transformed since the 2016 Presidential election with more people applying for asylum in Mexico than in the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] After the 2014 immigration crisis in America, the influx of immigrants from Central America to the United States continued but in lower proportions.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Over the early 2010s America and Mexico presented consistent pushback to all immigrants from Central America.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] America and Mexico both also showed no immediate immigration policy changes even with the crisis.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The United States and Mexico have militarized borders and dissuaded immigrants from making the journey as of 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Central American families and children kept coming to borders seeking asylum.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) and the Customs and Border Protection (CBP) detention of Central American people in the Mexican-American borders increased over 100 percent from late 2015 to early 2016 compared the year before.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Also, United States government ordered for the deportation in 7,700 in 2014 to 2015 without court hearings.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] There were 62,000 children still awaiting legal proceedings after 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In most cases, 94 percent of these children do not have attorneys to represent them in court.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] People from the Northern Triangle continued to immigrate despite the militarization of the CBP, increase in deportations, and the dangerous journey because their homes remain unsafe.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] During the 2011-2015 period, most migrants from Central America settled in California, followed by Texas and Florida.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Census data from 2010, out of the top 10 cities where Guatemalan Americans reside in the United States, three cities fall in California: Los Angeles, San Francisco/Oakland/Fremont, and Riverside/San Bernardino/Ontario.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Salvadoran Americans in the United States were in the highest concentrations in Los Angeles, Houston and New York in 2010, with 7 out of the top 25 cities with Salvadoran Americans falling in California.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In 2011, Honduran Americans in the United States were populated in the highest proportions in Florida, Texas, and New York.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] After arriving in the United States, these migrants fall into the legal category of undocumented aliens, which puts them at the risk of deportation.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Deportation to their home country poses further problems for Central Americans, as the NCTA countries are not prepared to deal with their return due to inadequacies in the physical and political infrastructure.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Kids in Need of Defense (KIND) provides free legal aid to unaccompanied minors in immigration proceedings across the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] KIND was founded in October 2008 by Angelina Jolie in a collaboration with the Microsoft Corporation and 25 leading U.S. law firms.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In addition to smaller organizations focused on assisting Central Americans in the United States, broader international organizations such as UNICEF, International Rescue Committee, Amnesty International also provide advocacy and support for Central Americans migrating to the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The matter was reported to be under investigation by the FBI.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In July 2015, a federal indictment revealed a forced-labor ring operating on an egg farm near Marion, Ohio, in which teenagers from Guatemala were being lured with promises of education and then forced to work 12-hour days, six or seven days a week.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The teens lived in squalid trailers, were denied their paychecks and threatened with death if they sought help.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] At least half a dozen of the teenagers found working on the farm had been in the custody of the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Department of Health and Human Services' (HHS) Office of Refugee Resettlement, which is charged with the processing, treatment, and placement of unaccompanied migrant children pending the resolution of immigration proceedings.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Government officials placed the teens with human traffickers who posed as relatives and friends.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Concerns that the Ohio case was indicative of larger, systemic problems led to a Senate inquiry into how human traffickers successfully exploited the federal resettlement processes.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The results of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations' probe were released on January 26, 2016.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Claire McCaskill (D-MO), the committee found that preventable mistakes were made in the Ohio case.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] HHS officials failed to run background checks on the sponsors and any secondary caregivers in the households, site visits to the sponsors' homes were not conducted, and in one instance a sponsor was permitted to prevent a child-welfare case worker from visiting with one of the victims.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] System-wide, the Senate inquiry found similar, serious gaps including weak processes for verifying relationships between children and sponsors, failure to perform background checks, lack of home visits and home studies, and the placement of children without meeting sponsors in person.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Other key deficiencies in HHS policies and procedures were an inability to detect when a sponsor is seeking custody of multiple unrelated children and allowing sponsors to deny HHS from providing post-release services to children and barring contact between HHS care providers and the children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Ultimately, the inquiry concluded that the policies for placing unaccompanied minors exposed them to a risk of trafficking and other abuse at the hands of government-approved sponsors.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The Subcommittee identified more than 10 other cases of post-placement trafficking beyond the Ohio case and 15 additional cases with "serious trafficking indicators." It is unclear how many other unaccompanied minors, placed by HHS, have been victims of trafficking or other abuses.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] HHS maintains no standardized mechanism of tracking trafficking or abuse cases.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Specifically, the government stopped fingerprinting most adults seeking to claim the children.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] Although the number of unaccompanied youth arriving from Central America declined significantly in 2015, with a 49% drop in the first 8 months of the year when compared to that same period in 2014, the number of young migrants is again on the rise.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] HHS officials stated that they are strengthening their policies and procedures for placing children and have signed a contract to open more shelters; however, they remain under pressure from the Senate Subcommittee and advocates to both account for documented failings and address their causes.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] In the discussion on the influx of Central Americans into the United States the terms "refugee" and "immigrant" have been used interchangeably or synonymously to represent Central Americans entering the country, despite the different legal ramifications of the two terms.
[src:american-humanist-association/2014-american-immigration-crisis] The difference in the usage of these terms comes from the different perspectives on the factors motivating movement to the United States, with "push" factors being associated with the terminology of "refugee" and "pull" factors being associated with the terminology of "immigrant".
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The **2016 Ecuador earthquake** occurred on April 16 at 18:58:37 ECT with a moment magnitude of 7.8 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (*Severe*).
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The very large thrust earthquake was centered approximately 27 km (17 mi) from the towns of Muisne and Pedernales in a sparsely populated part of the country, and 170 km (110 mi) from the capital Quito, where it was felt strongly.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The regions of Manta, Pedernales and Portoviejo accounted for over 75 percent of total casualties.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Manta's central commercial shopping district, Tarqui, was completely destroyed.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] There was widespread damage across Manabí Province, and structures hundreds of kilometres from the epicenter collapsed.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] At least 676 people were killed and 27,732 people injured.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] President Rafael Correa declared a state of emergency; 13,500 military personnel and police officers were dispatched for recovery operations.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Ecuador lies above the destructive plate boundary where the Nazca plate is subducting beneath the South American plate.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The convergence rate between the plates in Ecuador is 61 mm (2.4 in) per year.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The depth, location and focal mechanism of the earthquake are all consistent with rupture along the plate interface in the form of a megathrust earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] A major earthquake in 1906 ruptured the plate interface for at least 400 km (250 mi) immediately northeast of the 2016 event.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Finite fault model released by USGS for this event shows a 140 by 145 km (87 by 90 mi) rupture area.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] A paper from *Geophysical Research Letters* found a particular zone of high slip inside a 80 by 60 km (50 by 37 mi) patch of the broken subduction interface located at depths of between 15 and 44 km (9.3 and 27.3 mi).
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The rupture failed to propagate towards the trench; ceasing about 60 km (37 mi) away.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] A maximum slip of 2.5 m (8 ft 2 in) was estimated while the average slip across the rupture was 0.7 m (2 ft 4 in).
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The earthquake ruptured a part of the plate boundary that had previously ruptured in another magnitude 7.8 quake in 1942.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The similar aftershock distribution and rupture characteristics suggest the 2016 event was a repeat of the earthquake in 1942.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The 1942 earthquake marked the beginning of a supercycle of earthquakes re-rupturing the entire boundary previously broken during the large 1906 event.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The last earthquake in the supercycle occurred in 1979.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Another earthquake in 1958 also formed part of the supercycle.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] At 18:58 ECT on April 16, a 7.8 Mw earthquake struck the coast of Ecuador approximately 27 km (17 mi) south-southeast of Muisne, in the province of Esmeraldas, at a depth of 20.6 km (12.8 mi).
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Tremors were felt in neighboring Colombia and Peru; a clinic in Cali, Colombia, was evacuated as a precautionary measure.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] A tsunami alert was issued by the Pacific Tsunami Warning Center for Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Fiji, Panama, and Peru.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] This is the largest earthquake to strike Ecuador since the 1979 Tumaco earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] According to Mayor Gabriel Alcivar, much of the town of Pedernales, about 35 km to the south-southwest of the earthquake's epicenter, was leveled.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] In Guayaquil—approximately 300 km (190 mi) from the epicenter—an overpass collapsed on a car, killing the driver.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] In Manta the control tower of the airport was severely damaged; an Air Force officer was injured and the airport closed.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Six homes collapsed and many others lost power in the nation's capital city of Quito.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The earthquake was presaged by a magnitude 4.8 foreshock eleven minutes before the main quake struck, and followed by over fifty-five aftershocks in the first twenty-four hours.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] At least 676 people were killed and more than 16,600 others were injured in the earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] It was the worst natural disaster to hit Ecuador since the 1949 Ambato earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Over 300 fatalities occurred in the cities of Manta and Portoviejo, both of which are located in Manabí Province.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The number of fatalities was estimated as several hundred within thirty minutes of the earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] However, the media reported the number of fatalities as significantly lower than what actually happened and than what was estimated within thirty minutes as the figure of reported fatalities with time shows.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The number of injuries reported by media also remained below the ultimate count and below the correct estimate within 30 minutes by QLARM as seen in the next figure.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] By April 24, the fatality count had reached 654, and 8,340 had been reported as injured.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Estimates of fatalities are based on calculations of the damage to the built environment using the program QLARM.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Within minutes of an earthquake only its epicenter is known, not the extent of its rupture.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The USGS shake map for this event shown on this page depicts the extent of the rupture area as a rectangle.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] With the length of the rupture as outlined by the aftershocks, a map of the likely mean damage by the settlement can be calculated.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] This map takes into account what intensities have been reported to the USGS for this earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The numbers of fatalities and injured calculated theoretically, based on the damage map shown here, agrees well with the reported numbers.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The extent of the rupture can sometimes be known from aftershocks during the few hours following the main shock.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] In that case, maps of the intensity of shaking expected in each settlement may be calculated as in the figure below at the left for the 2016 Ecuador earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Based on this ground motion, the mean damage expected in each settlement is then calculated.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] These maps allow first responders to target heavily damaged area.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Large cities tend to have buildings more resistant to shaking than villages, therefore the damage is less for city dwellers than for villagers, on average.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] In Colombia, near the city of Cali, one miner died as a result of the earthquake, becoming the only reported death outside of Ecuador.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] In response to the earthquake, a state of emergency was declared throughout the country and the national guard was mobilized to assist in rescue and relief efforts.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Approximately 10,000 military personnel and 3,500 police officers were deployed.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] President Rafael Correa cut his trip to Italy short in order to return to Ecuador.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Hydroelectric dams and oil pipelines were shut down as a precautionary measure.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] On April 17 the International Charter on Space and Major Disasters was activated by UNITAR/UNOSAT on behalf of UN OCHA, thus providing for the charitable and humanitarian re-tasking of satellite assets.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] On April 20, a 6.1–6.2 magnitude aftershock struck 15 miles west of Muisne around 3:30 am, local time.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] José Joaquín de Olmedo International Airport in Guayaquil was also closed due to communication issues.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] A UNICEF representative reported that the government is considering relocating "one or two" towns in the aftermath of the earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] There were also concerns about the Zika virus outbreak and the risk of dengue fever for people displaced by the quake.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] Days after the earthquake, the country experienced difficulties distributing food and water to those in need, including the over 26 thousand survivors relocated to shelters.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] President Correa acknowledged that the poor infrastructure of the country might be to blame.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] The President estimated the damage at $3 billion, and has obtained credit from the World Bank, Inter-American Development Bank, and other sources, anticipated to reach a total of $2 billion; national sales tax has been raised as have income taxes on Ecuadorians.
[src:american-humanist-association/2016-ecuador-earthquake] On 30 June 2025, former vice president Jorge Glas was sentenced to 13 years' imprisonment for embezzling public funds related to recovery efforts following the earthquake.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:american-humanist-association/501-c-organization] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph was born and raised in Florida.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He was educated at Cookman Institute, then moved to New York City as part of the early Great Migration, leaving behind the discriminatory Jim Crow–era south.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] There he became convinced that overcoming racism required collective action and he was drawn to socialism and workers' rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He unsuccessfully ran for state office on the socialist ticket in the early 1920s, but found more success in organizing for African American workers' rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1963, Randolph was the head of the March on Washington, organized by Bayard Rustin, at which Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his "I Have a Dream" speech.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph inspired the "Freedom Budget", sometimes called the "Randolph Freedom budget", which aimed to deal with the economic problems facing the Black community.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] It was published by the Randolph Institute in January 1967 as "A Freedom Budget for All Americans".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Asa Philip Randolph was born April 15, 1889, in Crescent City, Florida, the second son of James William Randolph, a tailor and minister in an African Methodist Episcopal Church, and Elizabeth Robinson Randolph, a seamstress.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1891, the family moved to Jacksonville, Florida, which had a thriving, well-established African-American community.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's father taught him that color was less important than a person's character and conduct.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] His mother taught him the importance of education and of defending oneself physically against those who tried to hurt one or one's family, if necessary.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph remembered vividly the night his mother sat in the front room of their house with a loaded shotgun across her lap, while his father tucked a pistol under his coat and went off to prevent a mob from lynching a man at the local county jail.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Asa and his brother, James, were superior students.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] They attended the Cookman Institute in East Jacksonville, the only academic high school in Florida for African Americans.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Asa excelled in literature, drama, and public speaking; he also starred on the school's baseball team, sang solos with the school choir, and was valedictorian of the 1907 graduating class.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] After graduation, Randolph worked odd jobs and devoted his time to singing, acting, and reading.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Du Bois's *The Souls of Black Folk* convinced him that the fight for social equality was most important.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Barred by discrimination from all but manual jobs in the South, Randolph moved to New York City in 1911, where he worked odd jobs and took social sciences courses at City College.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1913, Randolph courted and married Lucille Campbell Green, a widow, Howard University graduate, and entrepreneur who shared his socialist politics.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] She earned enough money to support them both.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Shortly after Randolph's marriage, he helped organize the Shakespearean Society in Harlem.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] With them he played the roles of Hamlet, Othello, and Romeo, among others.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph aimed to become an actor but gave up after failing to win his parents' approval.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's background as a Shakespearean actor gave him a "deep, resonant voice" that he used to considerable effect in his speeches while his dignified, "courtly" bearing assisted with negotiations.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In New York, Randolph became familiar with socialism and the ideologies espoused by the Industrial Workers of the World.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He met Columbia University law student Chandler Owen, and the two developed a synthesis of Marxist economics and the sociological ideas of Lester Frank Ward, arguing that people could be free only if not subject to economic deprivation.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] At this point, Randolph developed what became his distinctive form of civil rights activism, which emphasized the importance of collective action as a way for Black people to gain legal and economic equality.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] To this end, he and Owen opened an employment office in Harlem to provide job training for southern migrants and encourage them to join trade unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Like others in the labor movement, Randolph favored immigration restriction.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He opposed African Americans' having to compete with people willing to work for low wages.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] But unlike other immigration restrictionists, he rejected the notions of racial hierarchy that became popular in the 1920s.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1917, Randolph and Owen founded *The Messenger* with the help of the Socialist Party of America.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] It was a radical monthly magazine that campaigned against lynching, opposed U.S. participation in World War I, and urged African Americans to resist being drafted, fight for an integrated society, and join radical unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Soon thereafter, the editorial staff of *The Messenger* became divided by three issues: the growing rift between West Indian and African Americans, support for the Bolshevik revolution, and support for Marcus Garvey's Back-to-Africa movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1919, most West Indian radicals joined the new Communist Party, while African-American leftists—Randolph included—mostly supported the Socialist Party.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The infighting left *The Messenger* short of financial support, and it went into decline.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph unsuccessfully ran on the Socialist Party ticket for New York State Comptroller in 1920 and for Secretary of State of New York in 1922.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's first experience with labor organization came in 1917, when he organized a union of elevator operators in New York City.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1919 he became president of the National Brotherhood of Workers of America, a union that organized among African-American shipyard and dock workers in the Tidewater region of Virginia.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The union dissolved in 1921 under pressure from the American Federation of Labor.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's greatest success came with the Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP), which elected him president in 1925.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] This was the first serious effort to form a labor institution for employees of the Pullman Company, a major employer of African Americans.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The railroads had dramatically expanded in the early 20th century, and the jobs offered relatively good employment at a time of widespread racial discrimination.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] But because porters were not unionized, most had poor working conditions and were underpaid.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Under Randolph's direction, the BSCP enrolled 51 percent of porters within a year, to which Pullman responded with violence and firings.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1928, after failing to win mediation under the Watson-Parker Railway Labor Act, Randolph planned a strike.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] This was postponed after rumors circulated that Pullman had 5,000 replacement workers ready to take the place of BSCP members.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] As a result of its perceived ineffectiveness, membership in the union declined; by 1933 it had only 658 members and electricity and telephone service at headquarters had been disconnected because of nonpayment of bills.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The American historian William Harris wrote: "Randolph functioned mainly as a symbolic figure and spokesman.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He was in the tradition of those Black leaders—they can be seen in the church and Black advancement organizations, as well as in politics—whose influence has derived largely from rhetoric and personal presence.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] But despite his superb rhetorical abilities and presence, Randolph was indecisive and prone to compromise".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Harris described Randolph as the most charismatic Afro-American leader of his generation, writing: "Handsome, almost exquisite in bearing, and a master of the arts of oratory and rhetoric, his speech had a hypnotic effect upon his audience.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The BSCP's fortunes changed with the 1932 election of President Franklin D.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] With amendments to the Railway Labor Act in 1934, porters were granted rights under federal law.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Membership in the Brotherhood jumped to more than 7,000.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] After years of bitter struggle, the Pullman Company began to negotiate with the Brotherhood in 1935, and agreed to a contract with it in 1937.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Employees gained $2,000,000 in pay increases, a shorter workweek, and overtime pay.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph maintained the Brotherhood's affiliation with the American Federation of Labor through the 1955 AFL-CIO merger.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Through his success with the BSCP, Randolph emerged as one of the most visible spokespeople for African-American civil rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He called shaping public opinion "the most powerful weapon in America" and by 1940 had become the face of the U.S. civil rights movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In September 1940, at the annual BSCP convention in Harlem, Randolph urged the Roosevelt administration to have no discrimination in the Selective Training and Service Act, which was being debated in Congress at the time.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was a speaker at the convention, and through her, Randolph obtained a meeting at the White House with President Franklin D.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] At the meeting, Roosevelt promised Randolph there would be no segregation in the military, saying he was sympathetic to the civil rights movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Two weeks later, the War Department issued a statement saying "the policy of the War Department is not to intermingle colored and white enlisted personnel".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Feeling betrayed, Randolph launched nationwide protests demanding the end of segregation in not only the military but also the industries that made weapons for it.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] At the time, the Roosevelt administration was gearing up to make the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] "the arsenal of democracy" by supplying a massive number of weapons to the United Kingdom and its allies that were fighting in World War II, and banning segregation in the defense-related industry would be a huge gain for the civil rights movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph told an aide: "I think we ought to have 10,000 Negros march down Pennsylvania Avenue...We shall not call upon our white friends to march with us.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] There are some things that Negros must do on their own".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1941, Randolph, Bayard Rustin, and A.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Muste proposed a march on Washington to protest racial discrimination in war industries, an end to segregation, access to defense employment, the proposal of an anti-lynching law, and the desegregation of the U.S. armed forces.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's belief in the power of peaceful direct action was inspired partly by Mahatma Gandhi's success using such tactics during the Indian independence movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph threatened to have 50,000 Black people march on Washington.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In early May 1941, Randolph made the call for a march on Washington, which generated immense enthusiasm among Afro-Americans.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] On 18 June 1941, Randolph again met with Roosevelt at the White House with the mayor of New York, Fiorello La Guardia, serving as a mediator.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Roosevelt asked Randolph to call off the march, saying "questions like this cannot be settled with a sledgehammer", and vaguely promised to have discussions if the march was canceled.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph said the march would not be canceled unless Roosevelt gave way.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] La Guardia broke the impasse by saying: "Gentlemen, it is clear that Mr.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph is not going to call off the march, and I suggest we all begin to seek a formula".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The march was canceled after Roosevelt issued Executive Order 8802, or the Fair Employment Act.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Some activists, including Rustin, felt betrayed because Roosevelt's order banned discrimination only in war industries, not the armed forces.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Nonetheless, the Fair Employment Act is generally considered an important early civil rights victory.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 read: "There shall be no discrimination in the employment of workers in defense industries or the government because of race, creed, color or national origin".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph dropped his demand for an integrated military, which he seems to have privately regarded as unrealistic and only made as a bargaining chip in his talks with Roosevelt.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The draft involved young men from all 48 states, and the bloc of conservative Southern whites in Congress would have fiercely fought an executive order for an integrated military.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] By contrast, most of the defense-related industry was in the Northeast, the Midwest, and California, so executive Order 8802 had only limited impact in the South.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The proposed march on Washington was a turning point in the civil rights movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] One Black newspaper wrote at the time, "it demonstrated to the Doubting Thomases among us that only mass action can pry open the doors that have been erected against America's Black minority".
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Before 1941, Black leaders had generally sought to lobby white politicians to change the laws.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] After 1941, there was a tendency to bypass politicians and instead engage in protests.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 led to an exodus of Black people out of the South comparable to the Great Migration of the early 20th century.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] For example, in every month of 1942, about 10,000 Afro-Americans from the South, mostly from Texas and Louisiana, settled in the Los Angeles area, to take jobs in the well-paying aviation industry.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The movement continued to gain momentum.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Unlike World War I, Randolph supported the war effort in World War II under the slogan "Double Victory", meaning victory over fascism abroad and racism at home.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1942, an estimated 18,000 Black people gathered at Madison Square Garden to hear Randolph kick off a campaign against discrimination in the military, war industries, government agencies, and labor unions.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1943, Randolph visited Memphis to launch a personal campaign for free speech after E.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Crump, a Democratic ally of Roosevelt, successfully used strong-arm and political pressure tactics to drive two prominent local Black Republicans, J.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Martin and Robert Church Jr., out of the city.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] After he came to Memphis, Crump denied Randolph venues and intimidated local Black leaders into declining speaking invitations by threatening them with jail.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] When Randolph urged Eleanor Roosevelt, who had friendly political ties with Crump, to do something to counter Crump's "fascist" denial of free speech, she refused.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Her reply to Randolph on December 18 read in full: "I referred your letter to a friend of mine when I received it and I am sorry it has not been answered before.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and other activists continued to press for African Americans' rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1947, Randolph and Grant Reynolds renewed efforts to end discrimination in the armed services, forming the Committee Against Jim Crow in Military Service, later renamed the League for Non-Violent Civil disobedience.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Truman asked Congress for a peacetime draft law, Randolph urged young Black men to refuse to register.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Truman was vulnerable to defeat in 1948 and needed the support of the growing Black population in northern states, and he capitulated.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] On July 26, 1948, Truman began ending racial segregation in the armed forces with Executive Order 9981.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1950, along with NAACP Executive Secretary Roy Wilkins and National Jewish Community Relations Advisory Council leader Arnold Aronson, Randolph founded the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights (LCCR), which became a major civil rights coalition.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] It coordinated a national legislative campaign on behalf of every major civil rights law since 1957.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and Rustin also formed an important alliance with Martin Luther King Jr. in 1957, when schools in the south resisted school integration after *Brown v.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and King organized the Prayer Pilgrimage for Freedom.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1958 and 1959, Randolph organized Youth Marches for Integrated Schools in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] At the same time, he arranged for Rustin to teach King to organize peaceful demonstrations in Alabama and form alliances with progressive whites.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The protests, directed by James Bevel in cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery, provoked violent backlash by police and the local Ku Klux Klan in 1963, which was captured on television and broadcast worldwide.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Rustin later said that Birmingham "was one of television's finest hours.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph finally realized his vision for a March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom on August 28, 1963.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] It attracted between 200,000 and 300,000 to the nation's capital.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The rally is often remembered as the high point of the Civil Rights Movement, and it did help keep the issue in the public consciousness.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] But when President Kennedy was assassinated three months later, civil rights legislation stalled in the Senate.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Johnson, the Civil Rights Act finally passed.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] King and Bevel deserve great credit for these legislative victories, but the importance of Randolph's contributions to the Civil Rights Movement is large.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph avoided speaking publicly about his religious beliefs to avoid alienating his diverse constituencies.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Though he is sometimes identified as an atheist, particularly by his detractors, Randolph identified with the African Methodist Episcopal Church he was raised in.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He pioneered the use of prayer protests, which became a key tactic of the civil rights movement.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] In 1973, he signed the *Humanist Manifesto II*.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph died in his Manhattan apartment on May 16, 1979.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] For several years before his death, he had a heart condition and high blood pressure.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] He had no known living relatives, as his wife Lucille had died in 1963, before the March on Washington.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Randolph had a significant impact on the Civil Rights Movement from the 1930s onward.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] The Montgomery bus boycott in Alabama was directed by E.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Nixon, who had been a member of the BSCP and was influenced by Randolph's methods of nonviolent confrontation.
[src:american-humanist-association/a-philip-randolph] Nationwide, the Civil Rights Movement in the 1950s and 1960s used tactics pioneered by Randolph, such as encouraging African Americans to vote as a bloc, mass voter registration, and training activists for nonviolent direct action.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow was a psychology professor at Cornell University, Brooklyn College, Brandeis University, The New School for Social Research, and Columbia University.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He stressed the importance of focusing on the positive qualities in people, as opposed to treating them as a "bag of symptoms".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] A *Review of General Psychology* survey, published in 2002, ranked Maslow as the tenth most cited psychologist of the 20th century.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Born in 1908 and raised in Brooklyn, New York, Maslow was the oldest of seven children.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] His parents were first-generation Jewish immigrants from Kyiv, then part of the Russian Empire (now Kyiv, Ukraine), who fled from Czarist persecution in the early 20th century.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] They had decided to live in New York City and in a multiethnic, working-class neighborhood.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] His parents were poor and not intellectually focused, but they valued education.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He had various encounters with antisemitic gangs who would chase and throw rocks at him.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He eventually developed a strong revulsion towards his mother.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He also grew up with few friends other than his cousin Will, and as a result, he grew up in libraries and among books.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] It was here that he developed his love for reading and learning.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He went to Boys High School, one of the top high schools in Brooklyn, where his best friend was his cousin Will Maslow.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Here, he served as the officer to many academic clubs and became editor of the Latin magazine.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He also edited *Principia,* the school's physics paper, for a year.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow attended the City College of New York after high school.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1926, he began taking legal studies classes at night in addition to his undergraduate course load.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He disliked it and almost immediately dropped out.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1927, he transferred to Cornell University but left after just one semester due to poor grades and high costs.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He later graduated from City College and went to graduate school at the University of Wisconsin to study psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1928, he married his first cousin, Bertha, who was still in high school.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The pair had met in Brooklyn years earlier.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's psychology training at University of Wisconsin was decidedly experimental-behaviorist.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] At Wisconsin, he pursued a line of research that included investigating primate dominance behavior and sexuality.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's early experience with behaviorism would leave him with a strong positivist mindset.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Upon the recommendation of professor Hulsey Cason, Maslow wrote his master's thesis on "learning, retention, and reproduction of verbal material".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow regarded the research as embarrassingly trivial, but he completed his thesis in the summer of 1931 and was awarded his master's degree in psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He was so ashamed of the thesis that he removed it from the psychology library and tore out its catalog listing.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] However, Cason admired the research enough to urge Maslow to submit it for publication.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's thesis was published as two articles in 1934.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow continued his research on similar themes at Columbia University.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] There he found another mentor in Alfred Adler, one of Sigmund Freud's early colleagues.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] From 1937 to 1951, Maslow was on the faculty of Brooklyn College.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] His family life and his experiences influenced his psychological ideas.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] After World War II, Maslow began to question how psychologists had come to their conclusions, and though he did not completely disagree, he had his own ideas on how to understand the human mind.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He called his new discipline humanistic psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow was already 33 years old and had two children when the United States entered World War II in 1941.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He was thus ineligible for military service.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] However, the war inspired a vision of peace in him, leading to his groundbreaking psychological studies of self-actualizing.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The studies began under the supervision of two mentors, anthropologist Ruth Benedict and Gestalt psychologist Max Wertheimer, whom he admired professionally and personally.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Being such "wonderful human beings" also inspired Maslow to take notes about them and their behavior.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This would be the basis of his lifelong research and thinking about mental health and human potential.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow extended the subject, borrowing ideas from other psychologists and adding new ones, such as the concepts of a hierarchy of needs, metaneeds, metamotivation, self-actualizing persons, and peak experiences.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He was a professor at Brandeis University from 1951 to 1969.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He became a resident fellow of the Laughlin Institute in California.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1967, Maslow had a serious heart attack and knew his time was limited.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He considered himself to be a psychological pioneer.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He pushed future psychologists by bringing to light different paths to ponder.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He built the framework that later allowed other psychologists to conduct more comprehensive studies.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow believed that leadership should be non-intervening.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Consistent with this approach, he rejected a nomination in 1963 to be the Association for Humanistic Psychology president because he felt the organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] While jogging, Maslow had a severe heart attack and died on June 8, 1970, at the age of 62 in Menlo Park, California.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Most psychologists before him had been concerned with the abnormal and the ill.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He urged people to acknowledge their basic needs before addressing higher needs and ultimately self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He wanted to know what constituted positive mental health.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Humanistic psychology gave rise to several different therapies, all guided by the idea that people possess the inner resources for growth and healing and that the point of therapy is to help remove obstacles to individuals' achieving them.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The most famous of these was client-centered therapy developed by Carl Rogers.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Humanistic psychology theory suits people who see the positive side of humanity and believe in free will.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This theory clearly contrasts with Freud's theory of biological determinism.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Another significant strength is that humanistic psychology theory is compatible with other schools of thought.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy is also applicable to other topics, such as finance, economics, or even in history or criminology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Humanist psychology, also coined *positive psychology*, is criticized for its lack of empirical validation and therefore its lack of usefulness in treating specific problems.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] It may also fail to help or diagnose people who have severe mental disorders.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Humanistic psychologists believe that every person has a strong desire to realize their full potential, to reach a level of "self-actualization".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The main point of that new movement, that reached its peak in the 1960s, was to emphasize the positive potential of human beings.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] However, Maslow was highly critical of Freud, since humanistic psychologists did not recognize spirituality as a navigation for our behaviors.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] To prove that humans are not blindly reacting to situations, but trying to accomplish something greater, Maslow studied mentally healthy individuals instead of people with serious psychological issues.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Self-actualizing people indicate a *coherent personality syndrome* and represent optimal psychological health and functioning.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This informed his theory that a person enjoys "peak experiences", high points in life when the individual is in harmony with themself and their surroundings.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In Maslow's view, self-actualized people can have many peak experiences throughout a day while others have those experiences less frequently.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He believed that psychedelic drugs like LSD and psilocybin can produce peak experiences in the right people under the right circumstances.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Self-actualizing people are more likely to have peak experiences.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In other words, these "peak experiences" or states of flow are the reflections of the realization of one's human potential and represent the height of personality development.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In later writings, Maslow moved to a more inclusive model that allowed for, in addition to intense peak experiences, longer-lasting periods of serene being-cognition that he termed *plateau experiences*.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He borrowed this term from the Indian scientist and yoga practitioner, U.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow stated that the shift from the peak to the plateau experience is related to the natural aging process, in which an individual has a shift in life values about what is actually important in one's life and what is not important.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In spite of the personal significance with the plateau experience, Maslow was not able to conduct a comprehensive study of this phenomenon due to health problems that developed toward the end of his life.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In studying accounts of peak experiences, Maslow identified a manner of thought he called "being-cognition" (or "B-cognition"), which is holistic and accepting, as opposed to the evaluative "deficiency-cognition" (or "D-cognition"), and values he called "Being-values".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow described human needs as ordered in a prepotent hierarchy—a pressing need would need to be mostly satisfied before someone would give their attention to the next highest need.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] None of his published works included a visual representation of the hierarchy.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The pyramidal diagram illustrating the Maslow needs hierarchy may have been created by a psychology textbook publisher as an illustrative device.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This now iconic pyramid frequently depicts the spectrum of human needs, both physical and psychological, as accompaniment to articles describing Maslow's needs theory and may give the impression that the hierarchy of needs is a fixed and rigid sequence of progression.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Yet, starting with the first publication of his theory in 1943, Maslow described human needs as being relatively fluid—with many needs being present in a person simultaneously.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The hierarchy of human needs model suggests that human needs will only be fulfilled one level at a time.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] According to Maslow's theory, when a human being ascends the levels of the hierarchy having fulfilled the needs in the hierarchy, one may eventually achieve self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Late in life, Maslow came to conclude that self-actualization was not an automatic outcome of satisfying the other human needs.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The first four levels are known as *deficit needs* or *D-needs*.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This means that if there are not enough of one of those four needs, there will be a need to get it.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Getting them brings a feeling of contentment.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow wrote that there are certain conditions that must be fulfilled in order for the basic needs to be satisfied.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] For example, freedom of speech, freedom to express oneself, and freedom to seek new information are a few of the prerequisites.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Any blockages of these freedoms could prevent the satisfaction of the basic needs.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy is used in higher education for advising students and for student retention as well as a key concept in student development.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's hierarchy has been subject to internet memes over the past few years, specifically looking at the modern integration of technology in people's lives and humorously suggesting that Wi-Fi was among the most basic of human needs.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow defined *self-actualization* as achieving the fullest use of one's talents and interests—the need "to become everything that one is capable of becoming".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] As implied by its name, self-actualization is highly individualistic and reflects Maslow's premise that the self is "sovereign and inviolable" and entitled to "his or her own tastes, opinions, values, etc." Indeed, some have characterized self-actualization as "healthy narcissism".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow realized that the self-actualizing individuals he studied had similar personality traits.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow selected individuals based on his subjective view of them as self-actualized people.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Some of the people he studied included Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln, and Eleanor Roosevelt.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] They were also "problem centered", meaning that they treated life's difficulties as problems that demanded solutions.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] These individuals also were comfortable being alone and had healthy personal relationships.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] They had only a few close friends and family rather than a large number of shallow relationships.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Self-actualizing people tend to focus on problems outside themselves; have a clear sense of what is true and what is false; are spontaneous and creative; and are not bound too strictly by social conventions.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow noticed that self-actualized individuals had a better insight of reality, deeply accepted themselves, others and the world, and also had faced many problems and were known to be impulsive people.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] These self-actualized individuals were very independent and private when it came to their environment and culture, especially their very own individual development on "potentialities and inner resources".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow based his theory partially on his own assumptions about human potential and partially on his case studies of historical figures whom he believed to be self-actualized, including Albert Einstein and Henry David Thoreau.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Consequently, Maslow argued, the way in which essential needs are fulfilled is just as important as the needs themselves.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Together, these define the human experience.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] To the extent a person finds cooperative social fulfillment, he establishes meaningful relationships with other people and the larger world.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In other words, he establishes meaningful connections to an external reality—an essential component of self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In contrast, to the extent that vital needs find selfish and competitive fulfillment, a person acquires hostile emotions and limited external relationships—his awareness remains internal and limited.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow used the term metamotivation to describe self-actualized people who are driven by innate forces beyond their basic needs, so that they may explore and reach their full human potential.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's theory of motivation gave insight on individuals having the ability to be motivated by a calling, mission or life purpose.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] It is noted that metamotivation may also be connected to what Maslow called B-(being) creativity, which is a creativity that comes from being motivated by a higher stage of growth.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Another type of creativity that was described by Maslow is known as D-(deficiency) creativity, which suggests that creativity results from an individual's need to fill a gap that is left by an unsatisfied primary need or the need for assurance and acceptance.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow based his study on the writings of other psychologists, Albert Einstein, and people he knew who [he felt] clearly met the standard of self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow used Einstein's writings and accomplishments to exemplify the characteristics of the self-actualized person.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Ruth Benedict and Max Wertheimer work was also very influential to Maslow's models of self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In this case, from a quantitative-sciences perspective there are numerous problems with this particular approach, which has caused much criticism.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] First, it could be argued that biographical analysis as a method is extremely subjective as it is based entirely on the opinion of the researcher.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Personal opinion is always prone to bias, which reduces the validity of any data obtained.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Therefore, Maslow's operational definition of Self-actualization must not be uncritically accepted as quantitative fact.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] During the 1960s Maslow founded with Stanislav Grof, Viktor Frankl, James Fadiman, Anthony Sutich, Miles Vich and Michael Murphy, the school of transpersonal psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow had concluded that humanistic psychology was incapable of explaining all aspects of human experience.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He identified various mystical, ecstatic, or spiritual states known as "peak experiences" as experiences beyond self-actualization.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow called these experiences "a fourth force in psychology", which he named transpersonal psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Transpersonal psychology was concerned with the "empirical, scientific study of, and responsible implementation of the finding relevant to, becoming, mystical, ecstatic, and spiritual states" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1962, Maslow published a collection of papers on this theme, which developed into his 1968 book *Toward a Psychology of Being*.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In this book Maslow stresses the importance of transpersonal psychology to human beings, writing: "without the transpersonal, we get sick, violent, and nihilistic, or else hopeless and apathetic" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Human beings, he came to believe, need something bigger than themselves that they are connected to in a naturalistic sense, but not in a religious sense: Maslow himself was an atheist and found it difficult to accept religious experience as valid unless placed in a positivistic framework.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In fact, Maslow's position on God and religion was quite complex.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] While he rejected organized religion and its beliefs, he wrote extensively on the human being's need for the sacred and spoke of God in more philosophical terms, as beauty, truth and goodness, or as a force or a principle.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Awareness of transpersonal psychology became widespread within psychology, and the *Journal of Transpersonal Psychology* was founded in 1969, a year after Abraham Maslow became the president of the American Psychological Association.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In the United States, transpersonal psychology encouraged recognition for non-western psychologies, philosophies, and religions, and promoted understanding of "higher states of consciousness", for instance through intense meditation.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Transpersonal psychology has been applied in many areas, including transpersonal business studies.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow called his work positive psychology.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Since 1968 his work has influenced the development of positive psychotherapy, a transcultural, humanistic based psychodynamic psychotherapy method used in mental health and psychosomatic treatment founded by Nossrat Peseschkian.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Since 1999 Maslow's work enjoyed a revival of interest and influence among leaders of the positive psychology movement such as Martin Seligman.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] This movement focuses only on a higher human nature.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Positive psychology spends its research looking at the positive side of things and how they go right rather than the pessimistic side.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1966, Maslow published a pioneering work in the psychology of science, *The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance*, the first book ever actually titled 'psychology of science'.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In this book Maslow proposed a model of 'characterologically relative' science, which he characterized as an ardent opposition to the *historically, philosophically, sociologically and psychologically naıve* positivistic reluctance to see science *relative to time, place, and local culture*.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Abraham Maslow is also known for Maslow's hammer, popularly phrased as "if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail" from his book *The Psychology of Science*, published in 1966.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's ideas have been criticized for their lack of scientific rigor.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He was criticized as too soft scientifically by American empiricists.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 2006, author and former philosophy professor Christina Hoff Sommers and practicing psychiatrist Sally Satel asserted that, due to lack of empirical support, Maslow's ideas have fallen out of fashion and are "no longer taken seriously in the world of academic psychology".
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Positive psychology spends much of its research looking for how things go right rather than the more pessimistic view point, how things go wrong.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The hierarchy of needs has furthermore been accused of having a cultural bias—mainly reflecting Western values and ideologies.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] From the perspective of many cultural psychologists, this concept is considered relative to each culture and society and cannot be universally applied.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] — Maslow, 'Motivation and Personality' (1970), p.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's concept of self-actualizing people was united with Piaget's developmental theory to the process of initiation in 1993.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow's theory of self-actualization has been met with significant resistance.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The theory itself is crucial to the humanistic branch of psychology and yet it is widely misunderstood.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The concept behind self-actualization is widely misunderstood and subject to frequent scrutiny.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow was criticized for noting too many exceptions to his theory.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] As he acknowledged these exceptions, he did not do much to account for them.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Shortly prior to his death, one problem he tried to resolve was that there are people who have satisfied their deficiency needs but still do not become self-actualized.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] He never resolved this inconsistency within his theory.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Social psychologist David Myers has pointed out Maslow's selection bias, rooted in the choice to study individuals who lived out his own values.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] If he had studied other historical heroes, such as Napoleon, Alexander the Great, and John D.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Rockefeller, his descriptions of self-actualization might have been significantly different.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Later in life, Maslow was concerned with questions such as, "Why don't more people self-actualize if their basic needs are met?
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In the spring of 1961, Maslow and Tony Sutich founded the *Journal of Humanistic Psychology*, with Miles Vich as editor until 1971.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] The journal printed its first issue in early 1961 and continues to publish academic papers.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] Maslow attended the Association for Humanistic Psychology's founding meeting in 1963 where he declined nomination as its president, arguing that the new organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader which resulted in useful strategy during the field's early years.
[src:american-humanist-association/abraham-h-maslow] In 1967, Maslow was named Humanist of the Year by the American Humanist Association.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage was born on July 15, 1967, in New York City.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He grew up in North Tarrytown (now Sleepy Hollow), a town in Westchester County about 25 miles (40 km) north of New York City.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He graduated from Sleepy Hollow High School in 1985.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His maternal grandfather, Cushman Haagensen, was a surgeon who pioneered breast cancer surgery.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His father, Whitney Lee Savage (1928–1998), was a painter, filmmaker, and animator known for his work on *Sesame Street* and *The Electric Company*, two nationally syndicated public television children's shows.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] The Clay Center in Charleston, West Virginia, features some of his work in its permanent collection.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Whitney Lee was also known for directing the 1969 underground short film *Mickey Mouse in Vietnam*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His mother, Karen, was a psychotherapist.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage was the second youngest of six children, with the four older children coming from his parents' previous marriages.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He has two older brothers, two older sisters, and one younger sister.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage began acting as a child and had five years of acting school.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His early credits include voicing animated characters that his father produced for *Sesame Street*, Mr.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Whipple's stock boy Jimmy in a Charmin commercial, and a drowning young man saved by a lifeguard in the 1985 Billy Joel music video "You're Only Human (Second Wind)".
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] "I had passed on that in favor of doing stuff with my hands," he said.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He describes *MythBusters* as "the perfect marriage of two things, performance, and special effects".
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] As a teenager in Sleepy Hollow, Savage routinely visited the local bike shop to have flat tires fixed.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] The shop showed him how to do the repairs himself.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] From this experience, Savage said, "I realized you could take a bike apart and put it back together and it wasn't that hard...
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage broke his neck on his eighteenth birthday in a swimming accident, an injury he survived without suffering long-term consequences.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage has worked as an animator, graphic designer, carpenter, projectionist, film developer, television presenter, set designer, toy designer, and gallery owner.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He worked as a model maker on *Galaxy Quest*, *Bicentennial Man*, *Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones*, *The Mummy*, *The Matrix Reloaded*, and *Space Cowboys*, among others.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He played the role of a helpful engineer in the 2001 film *Ever Since the World Ended*and the part of an army surplus store owner who sells a man a rocket engine for his pickup truck in the 2006 film *The Darwin Awards,* which also featured *MythBusters* co-star Jamie Hyneman.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage appeared with Hyneman on *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* on the May 1, 2008, episode "The Theory of Everything".
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He appears as a special effects artist in the "making of" material for *The Matrix Revolutions*, where he discusses some of the miniature effects used and the difficulties involved.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He previously taught advanced model making in the Department of Industrial Design at the Academy of Art University in San Francisco.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage has become a regular presenter at magician James Randi's annual skeptics conference The Amaz!ng Meeting since first appearing in January 2006.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He credits Michael Shermer with introducing him to the skeptical community.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Shermer interviewed him for *Skeptic Magazine* in 2006.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He appeared in the United Kingdom, giving a talk at the first Amaz!ng Meeting London in October 2009 hosted at the Mermaid Conference Centre, Blackfriars.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He was a featured performer at the three w00tstock v1.x shows in 2009 and appeared in four w00tstock v2.x shows in 2010.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He appeared as a guest on *Diggnation*'s 220th show.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage has been a regular guest speaker at the annual Maker Faire since 2008, speaking on different topics such as his obsession with the dodo bird and problem-solving, and taking questions from the audience members about *MythBusters*, among other topics.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He hosted an episode of the Discovery Channel series *Curiosity*, in which he speculated whether humans could live forever.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He discussed various topics during the program, such as limb regeneration, organ printers, and age reversal.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2011, he appeared as "Dan" in a short film directed by Frank Ippolito entitled *Night of the Little Dead*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] On November 25, 2011, he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Twente (Enschede, Netherlands) for popularizing science and technology.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage and Hyneman were judges on the game show *Unchained Reaction* which premiered in March 2012.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage is an occasional guest host for lecture events at the San Francisco-based non-profit City Arts & Lectures, and he delivered a keynote address at the South by Southwest conference on March 10, 2014.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] On March 24, 2012, he appeared as a featured speaker at the first Reason Rally in Washington D.C.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] On May 18, 2012, he was the commencement speaker at Sarah Lawrence College.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He co-hosts the weekly podcast *Still Untitled: The Adam Savage Project*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] The project launched on June 5, 2012, and is in the format of a conversation between Savage, tested.com editors-in-chief Will Smith and Norman Chan, and Simone Giertz about topics from science and movies to do it yourself and work ethics.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Episodes typically last 30 to 45 minutes.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage is a co-owner, editor, and contributor at tested.com.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2017, Savage toured with Michael Stevens on the Brain Candy LIVE! tour.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In April 2017, he played the role of a mission specialist in the episode *Caliban's War* of the series *The Expanse*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In June 2017, he was named "Humanist of the Year" by the American Humanist Association at their annual conference.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In October 2017, he played a cameo as a merchant selling blood bags in the *Blade Runner 2049* short film *2048: Nowhere to Run*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In April 2018, Discovery Channel announced that Savage would host and produce a new series called *MythBusters Jr.* which focused on a group of young scientists tasked with completing various experiments using STEAM skills.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In July 2018, he created and acted in the short film *A Farewell To Arms in collaboration with Weta Workshop*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] The same year, he won the Heinz Oberhummer Award for Science Communication.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In February 2020, SiliCon Valley Comic Con appointed him as its Creative Director, succeeding Steve Wozniak.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2022, Savage became godfather of the *Discovery Princess* cruise ship.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2023, he created a box for Isaac Newton's death mask held by the Royal Society.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage starred on *MythBusters* from 2003 to 2016.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His role with his co-hosts was to disprove or confirm myths through testing and experiments done at different scales.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] His demeanor on *MythBusters* is animated and energetic, providing a foil to Jamie Hyneman's more reserved straight-man persona.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage and Hyneman were the sole hosts of the show for the first season of *MythBusters*.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] They introduced members of Hyneman's staff in the second season, who began to appear regularly.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Kari Byron, Tory Belleci, and welder Scottie Chapman appeared in the second season.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In the third season, robot-builder and model-maker Grant Imahara replaced Chapman.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] *MythBusters* was filmed in San Francisco and edited in Artarmon, New South Wales.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] It aired 282 total episodes before its cancellation at the end of its 2016 season.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In November 2017, Discovery's sister network Science Channel revived the series with new hosts Jon Lung and Brian Louden.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2019, Savage hosted the spin-off series *Mythbusters Jr.*, featuring a team of teenagers skilled in STEAM topics.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In 2019, Savage published his first book, *Every Tool's a Hammer: Life Is What You Make It*, exploring his approach to making.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage married Julia Ward on September 11, 2004.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He has twin sons from a previous relationship.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He wears hearing aids in both ears due to congenital otosclerosis.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In the late 1980s, Savage lived at Eighth Avenue and Carroll Street in Park Slope, Brooklyn.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He later moved in with his parents for less than a year, working for a graphic design firm in Manhattan.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] A close friend living on Broderick Street in San Francisco asked him to become his roommate, and Savage moved to San Francisco in August 1990.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In a 2011 interview, Savage has publicly identified himself as an atheist.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In a 2019 Twitter post, he said he was an agnostic.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Regarding his relationship with Hyneman, he mentioned that although the two were not friends, they had mutual respect for each other, stating "We didn't care to say the truth to each other, because we didn't care if we hurt each other's feelings," he said.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Savage has a lifelong interest in costume making and cosplay.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] He stated, "I remember my mom getting me a *Jaws* costume when *Jaws* came out... and wearing a Batman costume.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Back then, everyone dressed up as hobos." He strives for authenticity with his costumes.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] While in high school, he and his father made a suit of armor out of aluminum roof flashing with seven hundred rivets.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] "I wore it to school and passed out from heat exhaustion in math class.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] In June 2020, Savage's younger sister, Miranda Pacchiana, filed a lawsuit against him, alleging that Savage had repeatedly raped her when they were both children.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] The siblings' mother came to Adam's defense, stating, "It makes me very sad to say this, but my daughter suffers from severe mental health challenges, and it's devastating that she's putting Adam and our entire family through this.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Adam is a good man, and I support him completely." The lawsuit was settled through mediation on May 24, 2021, and dismissed the next day.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Details of the settlement were not made public.
[src:american-humanist-association/adam-savage] Pacchiana removed her original blog post about Savage, which had precipitated the lawsuit.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The relationship between the terms depends on how *atheism* and *agnosticism* are defined.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] *Atheism* may refer broadly to the absence of theistic belief, but in philosophy of religion it is often used more narrowly for the proposition that God does not exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] *Agnosticism* may refer to suspension of judgment, or to the epistemological view that neither theism nor atheism is known.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Under the broader belief-and-knowledge distinction, agnosticism can be either atheistic or theistic because atheism and theism concern belief, while agnosticism concerns knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Under narrower philosophical definitions, however, atheism and agnosticism may be treated as distinct or mutually exclusive positions.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The distinction has been discussed by writers including Robert G.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Ingersoll, Robert Flint, Bertrand Russell, Antony Flew, George H.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Modern accounts have often framed the position in terms of evidential standards, the burden of proof, negative atheism, or probabilistic degrees of belief rather than as a simple claim of certainty or denial.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Agnostic atheism may be contrasted with agnostic theism, the view that one or more deities exist while their existence or nonexistence is unknown or cannot be known.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Agnostic atheism combines a negative or non-affirming form of atheism with an agnostic position about knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In this usage, *atheism* refers to the absence of belief that any deity exists, while *agnosticism* refers to the view that the existence or nonexistence of deities is not known, cannot be known, or has not been established.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The compatibility of atheism and agnosticism depends on the definitions being used.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] On the broader belief-and-knowledge distinction, a person may lack theistic belief while also denying knowledge or suspending judgment.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] On narrower philosophical definitions, atheism and agnosticism may instead be treated as distinct positions.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The historical background of agnostic atheism lies in the distinction between disbelief and claims to knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The term *agnosticism* was introduced by Thomas Henry Huxley in the nineteenth century to describe an epistemological attitude toward claims that were not, in his view, demonstrated or demonstrable.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Later writers applied this distinction to atheism, treating atheism as concerning belief and agnosticism as concerning knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Ingersoll, often called "The Great Agnostic", presented atheism and agnosticism as overlapping rather than mutually exclusive.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In 1885, Ingersoll stated that the agnostic says, "I do not know, but I do not believe there is any God", and that the atheist says the same.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The statement illustrates an early formulation of the distinction between not believing in God and claiming knowledge that God does not exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Scottish theologian and philosopher Robert Flint used the expressions "agnostic atheism" and "atheistic agnosticism" in his Croall Lecture for 1887–88, later published as *Agnosticism*.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Flint argued that atheism and agnosticism should not be treated as necessarily exclusive positions.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In Flint's account, a person who finds no adequate reason to believe in God may be described as an atheist, while a person who also holds that God's existence cannot be known or proved may be described as both an agnostic and an atheist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In 1976, Antony Flew argued in "The Presumption of Atheism" for using *atheism* in a negative sense unless sufficient reason had been given for belief in God.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Flew's argument gave a prominent philosophical formulation to the distinction between merely not accepting theism and positively asserting that God does not exist, a distinction later used in discussions of negative and positive atheism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Smith restated the belief-and-knowledge distinction in explicitly atheistic terms.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Smith argued that theism and atheism refer to the presence or absence of belief in a god, while agnosticism concerns knowledge; on this account, agnosticism is not a third alternative to theism and atheism, but may be either theistic or atheistic.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Later atheist writing also used probabilistic rather than strictly binary classifications.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In *The God Delusion* (2006), Richard Dawkins presented a seven-point scale of theistic probability, ranging from strong theism to strong atheism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] His sixth category, "de facto atheist", describes a person who does not claim certainty but regards God's existence as very improbable and lives on the assumption that God does not exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The scale illustrates a modern formulation of an atheistic position that falls short of a claim to certain knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Agnostic atheism is usually classified through a distinction between belief and knowledge.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Smith, theism and atheism concern the presence or absence of belief in a god, while agnosticism concerns knowledge; agnosticism may therefore be either theistic or atheistic.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Under this classification, agnostic atheism is the atheistic form of agnosticism, while agnostic theism is the corresponding theistic form.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In taxonomies that distinguish between negative and positive atheism, agnostic atheism is generally associated with negative atheism when it involves the absence of theistic belief without the further claim that no deities exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] By contrast, positive atheism involves the additional affirmation that God or gods do not exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] This distinction corresponds to the broader psychological sense of atheism, in which atheism may mean lacking theistic belief, rather than to the narrower philosophical sense in which atheism is the proposition that God does not exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] This classification is not universally accepted.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In philosophy of religion, atheism is often used for the proposition that God does not exist, while agnosticism may be used for suspension of judgment about that proposition.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] On that usage, agnosticism and atheism are more naturally treated as distinct answers to the question of whether God exists, rather than as compatible labels.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Some philosophers further distinguish agnostics from people who merely lack the concept of a deity or have never considered the question.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Graham Oppy, for example, distinguishes agnostics from "innocents", who neither believe that there are gods nor believe that there are no gods because they have not considered, or cannot consider, the question of whether gods exist.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] This distinction limits the classification of agnostic atheism to persons who have considered the question of divine existence, rather than to every case of absent theistic belief.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Agnostic atheism is commonly justified by an evidential or epistemic standard for belief.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] On this view, a person may withhold belief in deities because the available evidence is judged insufficient, while also declining to claim that no deities exist or that their nonexistence is known.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The position therefore rejects theistic belief without necessarily adopting the stronger claim associated with positive atheism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] A related rationale concerns the burden of proof.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] In "The Presumption of Atheism", Antony Flew argued that atheism should be understood negatively unless sufficient reason has been given for belief in God.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] This approach supports a distinction between not accepting theism and affirming that God or gods do not exist, a distinction also used in discussions of negative and positive atheism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Agnostic atheism fits most naturally with this negative sense of atheism, although philosophers who reserve *atheism* for the proposition that God does not exist may instead classify such a position as agnosticism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Related positions include ignosticism and theological noncognitivism, which question whether the term "God" or some statements about God are sufficiently meaningful to be judged true or false.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Such views are sometimes discussed alongside atheism and agnosticism, although some philosophers treat them as distinct from both.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Ayer, for example, argued that statements about God were not genuine propositions.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Anthony Kenny distinguished agnostics, who regard the claim "God exists" as uncertain, from theological noncognitivists, who regard discourse about God as meaningless.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Drange similarly distinguished atheism, agnosticism, and noncognitivism as separate positions.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] The term *agnostic atheism* is disputed because it depends on contested definitions of both atheism and agnosticism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Under the broad definition used by Smith and some other atheist writers, atheism concerns the absence of theistic belief, while agnosticism concerns knowledge; on that view, the two labels can be combined.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Under the narrower propositional usage described by Draper, atheism is the proposition that God does not exist, while agnosticism is the suspension of judgment about that proposition.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] On that usage, a person who lacks theistic belief but does not affirm that God does not exist may instead be classified as an agnostic.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Some philosophers therefore prefer to reserve *atheism* for the proposition that God does not exist, rather than for every absence of theistic belief.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] Oppy argues that, in philosophical usage, atheism is best understood as the view that there are no gods, while agnosticism is distinct from both theism and atheism.
[src:american-humanist-association/agnostic-atheism] This stricter usage conflicts with classifications that treat agnostic atheism as a straightforward combination of atheism and agnosticism.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The **American Humanist Association** (**AHA**) is a non-profit organization in the United States that advances secular humanism.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The AHA has several publications, including *The Humanist*, *Free Mind*, a peer-reviewed semi-annual scholastic journal, *Essays in the Philosophy of Humanism*, and TheHumanist.com.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The organization states that it has over 34,000 members.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1927, an organization named the "Humanist Fellowship" was founded during a gathering in Chicago.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1928, the Fellowship started publishing the *New Humanist* magazine with H.G.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The *New Humanist* was published from 1928 to 1936.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The first *Humanist Manifesto* was issued by a conference held at the University of Chicago in 1933.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Signatories included John Dewey, but the majority were ministers (chiefly Unitarian) and theologians.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] They identified humanism as an ideology that espouses reason, ethics, and social and economic justice.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] By 1935, the Humanist Fellowship had become the "Humanist Press Association", the first national association of humanism in the United States.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In July 1939, a group of Quakers, inspired by the 1933 *Humanist Manifesto*, incorporated the Humanist Society of Friends as a religious, educational, charitable nonprofit organization authorized to issue charters and train & ordain its own ministry.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Upon ordination, these ministers were then accorded the same rights and privileges granted by law to priests, ministers, and rabbis of traditional theistic religions.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1941, Curtis Reese led the reorganization and incorporation of the "Humanist Press Association" as the American Humanist Association.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Along with its reorganization, the AHA began printing *The Humanist* magazine.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The AHA was initially headquartered in Yellow Springs, Ohio, then San Francisco, California, and, in 1978, Amherst, New York.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Subsequently, the AHA moved to Washington, D.C.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1952, the AHA became a founding member of the International Humanist and Ethical Union (IHEU) in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The AHA was the first national membership organization to support abortion rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Around the same time, the AHA partnered with the American Ethical Union (AEU) to help establish the rights of non-theistic conscientious objectors to the Vietnam War.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In the late 1960s, the AHA also secured a religious tax exemption to support its celebrant program, allowing Humanist celebrants to officiate at weddings legally, perform chaplaincy functions, and enjoy the same rights as traditional clergy.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1991, the AHA took control of the Humanist Society, a religious Humanist organization that now runs the celebrant program.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] After this transfer, the AHA commenced the process of jettisoning its religious tax exemption and resumed its exclusively educational status.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Internal Revenue Service recognized the AHA as a nonprofit, tax exempt, 501(c)(3), publicly supported educational organization.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Membership numbers are disputed, but Djupe and Olson place it as "definitely fewer than 50,000." The AHA has over 575,000 followers on Facebook and over 42,000 followers on Twitter.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The AHA is the supervising organization for various Humanist affiliates and adjunct organizations.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The Black Humanist Alliance of the American Humanist Association was founded in 2016 as a pillar of its new "Initiatives for Social Justice".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Like the Feminist Humanist Alliance and the LGBT Humanist Alliance, the Black Humanist Alliance uses an intersectional approach to addressing Black community issues.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The Feminist Humanist Alliance (formerly the Feminist Caucus) of the American Humanist Association was established in 1977 as a coalition of women and men within the AHA to work toward the advancement of women's rights and equality between the sexes in all aspects of society.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Originally called the Women's Caucus, the new name was adopted in 1985 to represent all the caucus members and the caucus's goals.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Over the years, members of the Caucus have advocated for the passage of the Equal Rights Amendment and participated in various public demonstrations, including marches for women's and civil rights.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 1982, the Caucus established its annual Humanist Heroine Award, presenting the initial award to Sonia Johnson.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Others receiving the awards have included Tish Sommers, Christine Craft, and Fran Hosken.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2016, the Feminist Caucus reorganized as the Feminist Humanist Alliance as a component of their larger "Initiatives for Social Justice".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The LGBTQ Humanist Alliance (formerly LGBT Humanist Council) of the American Humanist Association is committed to advancing equality for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people and their families.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Paralleling the Black Humanist Alliance and the Feminist Humanist Alliance, the Council reformed in 2016 as the LGBTQ Humanist Alliance as a larger part of the AHA's "Initiatives for Social Justice".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2014, the American Humanist Association (AHA) and Foundation Beyond Belief (FBB) merged their respective charitable programs, Humanist Charities (established in 2005) and Humanist Crisis Response (established in 2011).
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] AHA's Executive Director Roy Speckhardt commented, "This merger is a positive move that will grow the relief efforts of the humanist community.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Now Foundation Beyond Belief's Disaster Recovery program serves as a focal point for the humanist response to major natural disasters and complex humanitarian crises worldwide.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The program coordinates financial support and trains humanist volunteers to help impacted communities.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The Disaster Recovery program is sustained through the ongoing partnership between FBB and AHA, and ensures that our community's efforts are centralized and efficient.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Between 2014 and 2018, Humanist Disaster Recovery has raised over $250,000 for victims of the Syrian Refugee Crisis, Refugee Children of the U.S.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Border, Tropical Cyclone Sam, the Nepal and Ecuadoran Earthquakes, Hurricane Matthew in Haiti, and Hurricanes Irma and Maria.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In addition to grants for recovery efforts, volunteers have also helped rebuild homes and schools in the following locations: Columbia, South Carolina, after the effects of Hurricane Joaquin, in Denham Springs, Louisiana and Houston, Texas, after the flooding from Hurricane Harvey.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The association launched the Appignani Humanist Legal Center (AHLC) in 2006 to ensure that humanists' constitutional rights are represented in court.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Through amicus activity, litigation, and legal advocacy, a team of cooperating lawyers, including Jim McCollum, Wendy Kaminer, and Michael Newdow, provides legal assistance by challenging perceived violations of the Establishment Clause.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The American Humanist Association has received media attention for its various advertising campaigns; in 2010, the AHA's campaign was said to be more expensive than similar ad campaigns from the American Atheists and Freedom From Religion Foundation.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2008, it ran ads on buses in Washington, D.C., that proclaimed "Why believe in a god?
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Just be good for goodness' sake", and since 2009, the organization has paid for billboard advertisements nationwide.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] One such billboard, which stated "No God...
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2010, it launched another ad campaign promoting Humanism, which *The New York Times* said was the "first (atheist campaign) to include spots on television and cable" and was described by CNN as the "largest, most extensive advertising campaign ever by a godless organization".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The campaign featured violent or sexist quotes from holy books, contrasted with quotes from humanist thinkers, including physicist Albert Einstein, and was largely underwritten by Todd Stiefel, a retired pharmaceutical company executive.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In November 2012, the AHA launched a national ad campaign to promote a new website, KidsWithoutGod.com, with ads using the slogans "I'm getting a bit old for imaginary friends" and "You're Not The Only One".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The campaign included bus advertising in Washington, DC, a billboard in Moscow, Idaho, and online ads on the family of websites run by Cheezburger and Pandora Radio, as well as Facebook, Reddit, Google, and YouTube.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Ads were turned down because of their content by Disney, Time for Kids and National Geographic Kids.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The American Humanist Association and the Washington Area Secular Humanists created the National Day of Reason in 2003.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In addition to serving as a holiday for secularists, the National Day of Reason was created in response to the unconstitutionality of the National Day of Prayer.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] According to the event organizers, the National Day of Prayer "violates the First Amendment of the United States Constitution because it asks federal, state, and local government entities to set aside tax dollar supported time and space to engage in religious ceremonies".
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Several organizations associated with the National Day of Reason have organized food drives and blood donations, while other groups have called for an end to prayer invocations at city meetings.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Other organizations, such as the Oklahoma and Minnesota Atheists, have organized local secular celebrations as alternatives to the National Day of Prayer.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Additionally, many individuals affiliated with these atheistic groups choose to protest the official National Day of Prayer.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2012, the American Humanist Association co-sponsored the Reason Rally, a national gathering of "humanists, atheists, freethinkers and nonbelievers from across the United States and abroad" in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The rally, held on the National Mall, had speakers such as Richard Dawkins, James Randi, Adam Savage, and student activist Jessica Ahlqvist.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] According to the *Huffington Post*, the event's attendance was between 8,000 and 10,000, while the *Atlantic* reported nearly 20,000.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The AHA also co-sponsored the 2016 Reason Rally at the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] The American Humanist Association has named a "Humanist of the Year" annually since 1953.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In 2021, Richard Dawkins said on Twitter, "In 2015, Rachel Dolezal, a white chapter president of NAACP, was vilified for identifying as Black.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Some men choose to identify as women, and some women choose to identify as men.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] You will be vilified if you deny that they literally are what they identify as.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] Discuss." After receiving criticism for this tweet, Dawkins responded by saying, "I do not intend to disparage trans people.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] I see that my academic 'Discuss' question has been misconstrued as such, and I deplore this.
[src:american-humanist-association/american-humanist-association] In response to these comments, the American Humanist Association retracted Dawkins' 1996 Humanist of the Year Award.
